    {
      "id": "c4963516626be10011b4ffa190e43bd8325d5c07",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 192,
        "name": "Brian Behlendorf",
        "email": "behlendorf1@llnl.gov",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-02-12 17:55:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1\n\n(2 comments)\n\nThis is definitely the right idea.  But let's see if we can't get better interfaces in place for ZFS for you to use.  Otherwise I fear we're just going to be back here in a year reworking it again.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "4ccc49ed839e531c40908c5f4b7f43c094cdadd7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-12 18:08:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nthanks for the idea Brian.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "3a175c44b16787b20a225928f6d22bb80f48c0fc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-16 10:57:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nBrian, any idea when that big change will be landed? the commit message says it's not for production yet?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "5d643db285a7a6f104b7e3b890de4cb77ef96efc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 192,
        "name": "Brian Behlendorf",
        "email": "behlendorf1@llnl.gov",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-02-17 18:16:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: -Code-Review\n\nAlex, my intention is to get 0.6.4 tagged and out the door as soon as possible (we're down to a dozen issue or so).  Once that's done I'd like to bring both the large block and ABD changes in to an 0.7.0 branch.  Both of these patches are fully functional but haven't seen as much real world run time as I'd like.  I want to get them in very early so we can shake out any issues which are introduced before the next tag.\n\nOn a related note it occurred to me the interfaces you need are almost exactly the same interfaces we need to support Direct IO in the ZPL.  For Direct IO we a get a 'struct iov_iter' from the VFS which maps pages in an applications address space for read/write.  If we added a dmu_write_iov()/dmu_read_iov() for Direct IO you could use that stable interface.  This way Lustre shouldn't be destabilized by any of the memory management work.  The interface itself would also be rigorously tested through the ZPL with xfstests.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "521f2f2c335c3b02e90fd02a7ce74eb828d470e9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-18 12:56:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nBrian, where can I look at dmu_write_iov() and dmu_read_iov(). I don't see them in the master branch nor in the commit you posted before.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "cc8108abe2e1733ba616ee3863756a5900127e55",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 479
      },
      "date": "2015-02-18 19:49:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nAlex, unfortunately dmu_write_iov() and dmu_read_iov() don't exist yet.  I was just commenting that it's exactly the sort of interface we need to write on the ZFS side to support O_DIRECT in the ZPL.  But since we don't yet support O_DIRECT that work hasn't happened yet...",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "e55620662cca25f1f3679223903eb35a329747c8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-19 05:41:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nok, then what would be you suggestion on the problem this patch is trying to address? wait for dmu_read_iov() or try to proceed as is? as for FALSE in dmu_buf_hold_array_by_bonus(): that's the idea behind the patch - to grab buffers (even non-filled) at the first loop where we map remote niobufs into local buffers, then fill them with actual I/O (if needed) concurrently.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "bec01152a78dada9d821804cb1f114ab2dc1e4fd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 479
      },
      "date": "2015-02-19 23:34:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nIt would be nice if we could avoid reworking this code multiple times so I'd personally be inclined to wait until ZFS provides an optimized interface for this.  Have you considered not trying to take a hold on the dbufs so early.  Instead call dmu_prefetch() to immediately issue the IO asynchronously, then latter in read_prep() do the dmu_buf_hold_array_by_bonus(..., TRUE) to handle blocking until it's done.  This would avoid the need for Lustre to directly manipulate zio's which is bit of this patch I find objectionable.  It's ask for trouble long term because that's something we might change internally.\n\n> FALSE in dmu_buf_hold_array_by_bonus()...\n\nRight, I just wanted to ensure the comment gets updated so that it correctly describes the code.  The bit describing that the current implementation passing TRUE isn't particularly clear.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "1f79c6ea648eb81443034c6aac5d6e305f1a944c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-20 20:37:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nthat would require quiet significant change in the API: ->dbo_bufs_get() is supposed to map remote niobuf to a set of pages and return the number of the pages while ->dbo_read_prep() operates on the final (full) set of the pages.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
